        <div><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"> Absor, Abashi, and other random Verant employees (who also probably have names beginning with "A") had a field day on the <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/cgi-bin/forumdisplay.cgi?action=topics&forum=Developer|APO|s+Corner&number=1">Developer's Corner</a> today.<br><br><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000153.html">Why is Stormfeather so rare?</a><br><blockquote><br>Players have timed this guy to a 19 hour spawn who sometimes skips. This, combined with Lodizal (an even rarer spawn) make it almost impossible to complete the Iceland map quest without days of mindless, boring waiting. I've heard reports of players sitting for 80 plus hours waiting for this guy. The quest already has one bottleneck with Lodizal as players must be lucky enough to be in on the kill, and also win the roll. The Stormfeather thing is excessive. Why should we have to sit around for countless hours to complete a quest? Could you maybe look into upping the spawn time, or perhaps at least change it from skipping spawns?<br><br><font face="Verdana" size=2 color="#a00000">While I didn't personally design the quest I have assisted players in it's completion with my play character. One friend doggedly camped the spawn location for over two days straight before obtaining the component it carries. Another friend put a bounty out for players who were hunting the normal spawns in the area, he paid a generous sum to the first person to tip him off when the creature appeared. I guess it's up to you how you want to play the game and how important each particular item is to your character.<br><br>It's a random spawn, not timed, and as you pointed out it can be very rare. The quest yields arguably the best facepiece in the game so I don't predict a reduction in the difficulty of obtaining it.<br><br>As a team I know we're committed to pushing the envelope in regards to what we can pull off contentwise. I feel we've made some significant enhancements lately that will enable us to provide even more compelling content in the near future. <br><br>- Steve Burke</font></blockquote><br><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000151.html">Theft of Thought not Thieving Enough?</a><blockquote><br>I figured i jump in with a spell question (hope Mr. Poe isnt to busy atm =)<br>Im using ToT on mobs one common thing seems to happen, the higher level the mob the less you receive back into your mana pool.<br><br>I can understand this from a resist point of view or whatever (personally i would rather it be a stable amount like harvest), but my question is this;<br><br>Does the gain back into ones mana bar refloect how much was taken from the mob? Or do you always take a set amount from the mob, its just how much you receive that is level dependant?<br><br>Thanks<br><br><font face="Verdana" size=2 color="#a00000">Theft of Thought takes a set amount of Mana from your target and returns it to you. This amount scales up as you level. The numbers will be the same for both sides, meaning if you take 100 mana from the target you will get 100 mana. The mana stolen, and the mana returned are both level dependant.<br><br>- Lawrence Poe</font></blockquote><br><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/ubb/everquest/Forum1/HTML/000152.html">Questing for XP, not loot (long)</a><blockquote><font face="Verdana" size=2 color="#a00000"><br>Hi Relbeek,<br><br>After reading your email I think you're either a bit psychic or you've had our meeting room bugged.<br><br>Seriously, we've had a few discussions lately that have resulted in some changes being made. These changes will enable us to implement some of the suggestions you've made here, as well as some not mentioned such as quests that players can only do once in their lifetime. <br><br>We're all working on creating more original, compelling content with enticing rewards.<br><br>- Steve Burke</font></blockquote> </font>
